07050nam a22006975i 9781503619470DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222002cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036194707 a10.1515/97815036194702doi  a(DE-B1597)582636  a(OCoLC)1322124913  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSCI0340002bisacsh00aFrom Energy to Information :bRepresentation in Science and Technology, Art, and Literature /ced. by Bruce Clarke, Linda Dalrymple Henderson. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (464 p.) :b90 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWriting Science00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- tFrom Thermodynamics to Virtuality -- tPart One The Cultures of Thermodynamics -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Time Discovered and Time Gendered in Victorian Science and Culture -- t2. Dark Star Crashes: Classical Thermodynamics and the Allegory of Cosmic Catastrophe -- t3. Energetic Abstraction: Ostwald, Bogdanov, and Russian Post-Revolutionary Art -- tPart Two Ether and Electromagnetism: Capturing the Invisible -- tINTRODUCTION -- t4. Lines of Force, Swirls of Ether -- t5. The Real and the Ethereal: Modernist Energies in Eliot and Pound -- t6. Vibratory Modernism: Boccioni, Kupka, and the Ether of Space -- tPart Three Traces and Inscriptions: Diagramming Forces -- tINTRODUCTION -- t7. Representation on the Line: Graphic Recording Instruments and Scientific Modernism -- t8. Concerning the Line: Music, Noise, and Phonography -- t9. Bodies in Force Fields: Design Between the Wars -- tPart Four Representing Information -- tINTRODUCTION -- t10. On the Imagination's Horizon Line: Uchronic Histories, Protocybernetic Contact, and Charles Babbage's Calculating Engines -- t11. Escape and Constraint: Three Fictions Dream of Moving from Energy to Information -- t12. Cybernetics and Art: Cultural Convergence in the 1960s -- tPart Five Voxels and Senseis: Bodies in Virtual Space -- tINTRODUCTION -- t13. Authorship and Surgery: The Shifting Ontology of the Virtual Surgeon -- t14. Eversion: Brushing against Avatars, Aliens, and Angels -- tPart Six Representation from Pre- to Post-Modernity -- tINTRODUCTION -- t15. Puppet and Test Pattern: Mechanicity and Materiality in Modern Pictorial Representation -- t16. Dinosaurs and Modernity -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book offers an innovative examination of the interactions of science and technology, art, and literature in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. Scholars in the history of art, literature, architecture, computer science, and media studies focus on five historical themes in the transition from energy to information: thermodynamics, electromagnetism, inscription, information theory, and virtuality. Different disciplines are grouped around specific moments in the history of science and technology in order to sample the modes of representation invented or adapted by each field in response to newly developed scientific concepts and models. By placing literary fictions and the plastic arts in relation to the transition from the era of energy to the information age, this collection of essays discovers unexpected resonances among concepts and materials not previously brought into juxtaposition. In particular, it demonstrates the crucial centrality of the theme of energy in modernist discourse. Overall, the volume develops the scientific and technological side of the shift from modernism to postmodernism in terms of the conceptual crossover from energy to information. The contributors are Christoph Asendorf, Ian F. A. Bell, Robert Brain, Bruce Clarke, Charlotte Douglas, N. Katherine Hayes, Linda Dalrymple Henderson, Bruce J. Hunt, Douglas Kahn, Timothy Lenoir, W. J. T. Mitchell, Marcos Novak, Edward Shanken, Richard Shiff, David Tomas, Sha Xin Wei, and Norton Wise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh1 aAsendorf, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Ian F. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrain, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDalrymple Henderson, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayles, N. Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenderson, Linda Dalrymple, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHunt, Bruce J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahn, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLenoir, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, W. J. T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNorton Wise, M, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNovak, Marcos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShanken, Edward A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShiff, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTomas, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aXin Wei, Sha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford Univer